### `curl` Command for Sign-Up

```bash
curl -X POST http://localhost:8081/api/auth/v1/signup \
-H "Content-Type: application/json" \
-d '{
 "firstName": "john",
 "lastName": "Jis",
 "password": "pass",
 "userName": "dan",
 "email": "sss@gmail.com",
 "isVerified": false
}'
```

### Explanation:

- **`-X POST`**: Specifies that this is a POST request.
- **`http://localhost:8081/api/auth/v1/signup`**: The URL of your sign-up endpoint.
- **`-H "Content-Type: application/json"`**: Sets the `Content-Type` header to `application/json`, indicating that the request body contains JSON data.
- **`-d '{...}'`**: The `-d` flag is used to send the specified data in the request body. The data is formatted as a JSON object containing the user's details.

### Notes:

- Ensure your backend server is running and accessible at `localhost:8081`.
- The JSON data in the `-d` flag should match the expected structure of your `SignUpUserDto` class.
- If you encounter any issues, check the server logs for more detailed error messages.
- You can adjust the values in the JSON object as needed to test different scenarios.

This `curl` command will help you verify that the sign-up endpoint is working correctly and that the server is processing the request as expected."}],"context":{"currentFile":{"path":"src\main\java\org\example\infrastructure\adapter\input\controller\AuthController.java","fsPath":"C:\Users\DELL USER\Desktop\pigin\src\main\java\org\example\infrastructure\adapter\input\controller\AuthController.java","sources":["opened_tab"],"content":"package org.example.infrastructure.adapter.input.controller;

